<2ND_LINE>AM-Bodies Found,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four People Die From Carbon Monoxide Poisoning While Waiting In
Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men and two teen-age girls, whose bodies
were found Saturday morning in a truck with its engine running in
the woods, died of carbon monoxide poisoning, an autopsy showed.
   ``It's just a sad and very unfortunate accident,'' said District
Attorney John Conte.
   The four victims were in a four-wheel drive truck that apparently
was climbing a dirt hill and became stuck, said state Trooper Robert
C. Meier.
   Meier said the exhaust pipe was clogged with mud, which could
have caused the fumes to fill the truck and cause asphyxiation.
   ``Speculation is that they tried to get out of the mud and
decided to wait until morning. The right rear tire had blown,''
Conte said.
   He added that he doubted alcohol was involved.
   Dr. John Krolikowski completed autopsies at the University of
Massachusetts Medical Center about 5:30 p.m. Saturday, Conte said.
   The victims were identified as Kimberly McNeill, 18, of Upton;
Darlene Whitney, 17, of Grafton; Douglas Scobie, 25, of Hopkinton;
and Hans Rosenberger, 24, of Mendon.
   Conte said a hunter discovered the victims' bodies about 7:45
a.m. Saturday in Upton State Forest.
</TEXT>
