<2ND_LINE>AM-Subway Sale, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0591,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yuppies Flock To Subway Auction</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf with 3 grafs to UPDATE with final sales total,
quote. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `A couple ... '</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Throngs of people turned out Saturday for a
chance to buy buckets of conductors' badges, a bus odometer, old
signs and even an old subway car when the Transit Authority threw a
garage sale.
   ``I guess a lot has to do with memories,'' said Alan Unger of
Brooklyn, one of the lucky 2,000 who gained admission, for $5, to
the Transit Authority auction and ``tag sale'' of subway memorabilia.
   Unger, a medical investigator for the city's Health and Hospitals
Corporation, shelled out $16 for two 6-foot-long signs and two
subway photographs.
   For $90, Chris McGovern, a Solomon Brothers employee and
Manhattan resident, became the proud owner of an old roll sign,
reading ``Nassau Street.''
   ``It seems like this is a good piece of nostalgia for the
price,'' said McGovern.
   The proceeds, which amounted to $48,788, will go into for the
authority's general fund.
   The sale raised about $20,000 more than expected, said Gail
Dawson, deputy director of the Transit Museum, which gets part of
the proceeds.
   ``Volume was really good for the tag sale,'' Ms. Dawson said. ``I
don't know, people love this stuff.''
   A couple of subway workers rolled their eyes with disbelief while
buyers sifted through piles of rusty signs.
   ``Warning: Do Not Lean Over Edge of Platform,'' read one priced
at $150.
   The crowd snaked outside the subway museum, housed in a former
subway station in Brooklyn, and about 1,000 of them never got in.
   ``The line went all the way around the block. I nearly fell
over,'' said Jared Lebow, another transit spokesman.
   ``We're crazy,'' said JoAnne Martinez of Queens, who had been
waiting for 40 minutes.
   Her husband, Ray, a Police Department mechanic, hoped to buy some
of the Transit Authority badges tagged at $3 to $5 apiece.
   At the auction, Arthur Green, an entrepreneur from Woodstock,
N.Y., paid $3,000 for the 1937 subway car. He'll move it by flatbed
truck to Kingston, N.Y., where he plans to open a railroad exhibit.
   A solid oak ticket chopper, circa 1920, sold for $1,650. In those
days, passengers bought a ticket for a nickel, then a transit worker
pulled a lever to cut it in half as they entered the subway.
   A 4-foot-long, blue and white, oak-framed, circa 1920 sign that
read ``Interborough Rapid Transit Co.'' fetched $850. It used to
hang in the office of Transit Authority President David Gunn.
   A blue mosaic, bearing an ``H'' from the now-renovated Hoyt
Street station in Brooklyn, went for $850, while a snappy,
red-white-and-blue uniform from the defunct Transit Authority
marching band brought $250.
</TEXT>
