<2ND_LINE>BC-Alabama Tornado,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Possible Tornado Causes Property Damage; Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe weather early Sunday in this
western Alabama city damaged houses, downed power lines and injured
an undetermined number of people, authorities said.
   J. Danny Cooper, director of the Alabama Emergency Management
Agency, said a tornado apparently touched down in Tuscaloosa about
12:45 a.m.
   However, Joe Wheeler, a meteorologist with the National Weather
Service in Birmingham, could not immediately confirm the tornado
report. He said an inspection would determine whether a twister
caused the damage.
   Cooper said it was difficult to immediately assess the damage
since the storm hit in the middle of the night and knocked out power
in much of the area.
   ``I would say it would be in the morning before we'll know the
total number of people injured,'' Cooper said from his agency's
Montgomery headquarters. ``This is very difficult situation in the
dead of the night.''
   A Tuscaloosa police dispatcher who refused to give her name said
people were hurt but she did not know how many or the seriousness of
their injuries.
   Tuscaloosa County was under a severe thunderstorm warning when
the tornado was reported.
   Cooper said Gov. Guy Hunt had authorized the Alabama National
Guard to provide emergency lights and generators to aid rescue
workers, who were moving door-to-door to assess the damage.
