<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-88 1123EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomelessArt     11-20 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Art,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arts Project For the Homeless Builds Self-Esteem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new program to bring arts to homeless people
will help them build self-esteem and allow them to express what it's
like to be forced to tolerate the intolerable, sponsors say.
   ``Art is a socially acceptable means of communicating very strong
feelings,'' said Nancy Kirk, associate director of Omaha's
Metropolitan Arts Council.
   ``People who live in shelters need to be able to express very
powerful emotions in a way other than screaming.''
   The council has teamed with a coalition of local groups for the
homeless to provide workshops at seven homeless shelters in Omaha
and one in nearby Council Bluffs, Iowa.
   The experiment includes performances as well as opportunities for
homeless people to paint, sculpt, write and act. Eventually, the
council hopes to organize an exhibit of works by homeless people and
will also use the artworks to brighten the shelters.
   Omaha's homeless population is estimated to vary between 400 and
about 1,000, city officials said.
   When someone first mentioned the idea of arts for the homeless,
members of the council laughed, organizers recalled.
   ``We thought, `What would we do? Have port-o-arts kits? Or
strolling minstrels along the river banks?''' said Eleanor Jones,
the council's program coordinator.
   ``All of us were very naive. We thought the homeless were bums on
river banks,'' she said.
   Susan Ogborn, chairwoman of the Coalition for the Homeless, said
shelter residents have responded enthusiastically to the program,
which held its first performance last month.
   ``We started brain-storming last spring about what it is that
makes for a whole and healthy person,'' Ms. Ogborn said. ``Of
course, we thought of food and shelter and job training, but we also
thought of building self-esteem. A lot of that comes back to the
arts.''
   The Rev. Bob Timberlake, director of Omaha's Open Door Mission,
said the first performance at his shelter, involving a pair of folk
singers, was a great success.
   ``It helps them see beyond the tragedy. The homeless are so
filled with despair and emptiness. This helps to fill the vacuum,''
he said.
   ``It was a real treat,'' said Bruce Smith, 27, a resident of the
mission.
   James Bryant, 23, a Louisiana man who came to Omaha looking for
carpentry work, said the show he saw at the Day House was
``something different for the kind of situation we are in.''
   ``Most of the people here are kind of running short on money and
don't have anyplace they could go to see something like that,'' he
said.
   Critics of the homeless arts program feared it would be a
high-society wine-and-cheese party thrown on behalf of the
disadvantaged, sponsors said.
   ``When it first came out in the media it sounded like we were
trying to raise $50,000 or $60,000 to put on some extravagant arts
project, so there was an understandable backlash,'' Ms. Ogborn said.
Instead of government funds, the program is being run on $4,000
raised so far in private donations.
   Some contributors, Jones said, question the need for arts
programs for people who don't even have food and shelter, but she
has a ready response.
   ``I do feel that everybody has a right to a full-life experience,
even if it is just for one day,'' she said.
   Artists have a special ability to relate to the plight of the
homeless, Jones said.
   ``When you put something down on canvas or sculpt something, it
is you. It is your life and soul. You often are liable to great
criticism,'' she said.
   ``Artists are not in the mainstream of society. They sort of
understand what it is like not to be a mainstream person.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
