<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-USMilitary     11-20 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US Military,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Captain Reassigned After Shells Nearly Hit Japanese Vessel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of an American destroyer has been
relieved of his command, military officials said Sunday, less than
two weeks after shells fired from the captain's warship reportedly
came close to hitting a Japanese vessel.
   Frederick H. Michaelis Jr., commander of the USS Towers since
1987, was reassigned effective Nov. 19, said Marine Master Gunnery
Sgt. Jake Rodriguez, a military spokesman.
   Rodriguez did not give a reason for the move. He said more
details would be released after a Navy inquiry.
   On Nov. 9, the Towers was holding firing practice about 10 miles
off Boso peninsula east of Tokyo. The destroyer fired 10 rounds of
non-explosive, sand-filled projectiles from its 127mm guns that
landed as close as 330 yards from the Japanese coast guard patrol
boat Uraga, news reports said.
   No injuries or damage were reported, but Japanese authorities
have been demanding Michaelis resign. Michaelis will be assigned
temporarily to Destroyer Squandron 15, Rodriguez said.
   In another incident, clouds of irritating gas from an apparent
explosive device wafted over a residential area near Kadena Air Base
in Okinawa at about midnight Saturday, sending scores of crying,
choking people into the streets, police said.
   The officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said residents
complained of burning in their eyes and throats after what was
described as a tear gas-like substance hit a neighborhood in
Chatancho after making a loud popping sound.
   Fragments from an apparent explosive device were found in 35
spots around the area neighboring the American base, he added.
   The officer said police were told by U.S. officials that
colorless canisters the size of Coca-Cola cans are used by the air
base during practice, but that they make little noise upon impact,
unlike those that Chatancho residents heard.
   The U.S. military in Japan has suffered a series of accidents
recently that involved the public.
   In October, rifle bullets hit a civilian housing area near a
firing range on Okinawa. Earlier this month, two U.S. Marine
helicopters collided in flight over the island, killing four Marines.
   An editorial in the Asahi Shimbun, Japan's second-largest
newspaper, quoted Okinawa Gov. Junji Nishime as blaming the
accidents there on ``something wanting in the U.S. military's chain
of command or a decline of discipline.''
   About 46,000 U.S. troops are stationed in Japan under the
U.S.-Japan mutual security pact.
</TEXT>
