<2ND_LINE>AM-Mock Hanging,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fraternity Apologizes For Racial Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fraternity has apologized for a mock
hanging at Centre College that had racial overtones and members said
they are waiting for their punishment.
   ``There is no excuse for our lack of foresight,'' Lee D. Tatum,
president of Centre's Kentucky Alpha-Delta chapter of the Phi Delta
Theta fraternity, said in a statement Friday.
   ``We should have realized how this action would be interpreted,
and we are thoroughly embarrassed by our lack of sensitivity.''
   The 46-member fraternity, which has been on campus since 1850,
also hung a banner of apology outside a dining hall at the center of
campus.
   The mock hanging on Nov. 10 is an annual prank conducted around
Halloween, said Art Jester, director of college relations.
   While about 40 students and fraternity members watched, one
volunteer Phi Delta Theta member was placed in a mountain-climbing
harness attached to a tree by a rope, Jester said.
   The volunteer, whose face was blackened with burned cork, swung
about six feet above ground, without injury. Five people wearing
robes _ four gold and one black _ carried torches during the
15-minute ceremony.
   ``We are painfully aware of the way this incident has been
perceived by a large number of people,'' Tatum said. ``It was in no
way our intention to symbolically represent anything derogatory
toward any person or group of people.''
   Of the 860 students who attend Centre, a private university in
central Kentucky, 10 are black Americans and three are African. The
college has no black instructors.
   Dr. Ray Hammond, vice president and dean of students, will decide
upon the punishment, Jester said. He could not elaborate on what the
punishment would be or when it would take effect.
</TEXT>
