<HEAD>Thousands Demonstrate In Memory Of Franco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of flag-waving Spaniards held an
anti-government demonstration in downtown Madrid on Sunday to
commemorate the 13th anniversary of the death of Gen. Francisco
Franco.
   The demonstration, led by Carmen Franco Polo, the only daughter
of Franco, was organized by a veterans group that includes men who
fought with Franco against the second Republic during the 1936-39
Spanish Civil War.
   Organizers estimated the crowd at 150,000, but the municipal
police said only 20,000 attended.
   Demonstrators shouted slogans in favor of Franco and his regime
and against the government of socialist Prime Minister Felipe
Gonzalez.
   Giving the fascist salute, the protesters shouted, ``Franco,
Franco, Franco!'' and ``Long live Franco!''
   Irene Fernandez, spokeswoman for the Madrid provincial governor's
office, said the demonstrators dispersed without incident after the
90-minute protest.
   After his forces won the Spanish Civil War, Franco established an
authoritarian regime that ended with his death at age 83 on Nov. 20,
1975.
   Demonstrators placed bouquets of flowers on a statue of Franco in
front of the Transportation Ministry in Madrid. The demonstration
was the only one held in Spain, and many people attended from other
cities.
</TEXT>
