<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-88 1443EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChicagoMayoral     11-20 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0787</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fight to Succeed Washington Becomes Part of His Legacy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One year after Mayor Harold Washington's death,
there is pessimism in the black community that worshiped him and the
strong prospect of another Daley occupying City Hall come next
spring.
   When Washington was stricken by a heart attack Nov. 25, two days
before his 66th birthday, it marked the second time in 11 years that
a powerful Chicago mayor died in office without warning.
   And like the politician he came most to resemble _ ``Boss''
Richard J. Daley, who died in 1976 _ Washington died without
annointing a successor.
   ``Both were so jealous of power,'' said Alderman Larry Bloom, a
staunch Washington ally and one of a handful of announced candidates
for mayor, ``they made sure that nobody, but nobody, was on their
heels.''
   On Monday, the Illinois Supreme Court is scheduled to decide
whether to order a special election next year or allow acting Mayor
Eugene Sawyer to finish Washington's second term and face
re-election in 1991.
   If a lower-court ruling stands, 1989 will be the time and an
already crowded field is expected to swell as both Sawyer and Cook
County State's Attorney Richard M. Daley formally announce their
candidacies.
   The two are favored to meet in the Democratic primary Feb. 28,
although political observers say the 54-year-old Sawyer has the
tougher road to travel. In this strongly Democratic town where no
Republican has been mayor for more than a half-century, the primary
is considered decisive.
   If he wants to avoid a possibly fatal split in the black primary
vote, Sawyer will have to persuade Alderman Tim Evans, who leads him
in the polls, to drop out before the primary. Daley, the 46-year-old
son of the late mayor, is expected to have an easier time persuading
two of his three white rivals to step aside, while Bloom, the third
rival, is not considered much of a factor.
   Ironically, it was Daley who helped put Washington in office as
the city's first black mayor, by splitting the white vote with
then-incumbent Mayor Jane Byrne in the 1983 Democratic primary.
Washington gained a narrow primary victory against Daley and Byrne
before going on to win the general election that year. He then
repeated his win in the spring of 1987.
   Just as in 1983, the primary could be decided next February by
how many black or white candidates remain in the field. And this
time, the more costly struggle is taking place among the black
candidates.
   ``By electing Harold and then re-electing him, we gave ourselves
the impression we had become more sophisiticated politically,'' said
Lu Palmer, an influential local radio commentator and political
activist. ``Now, we are proving we did not.''
   According to a recent poll by the Chicago Sun-Times and WLS-TV,
Evans was supported by 45 percent of black voters, against 16
percent for Sawyer. A third black candidate, Alderman Danny Davis,
managed just 8 percent support. Blacks make up about 40 percent of
the population.
   When Daley is factored in, the same poll shows the late mayor's
son supported by 37 percent of all voters, including 13 percent of
blacks and 53 percent of whites. Evans was second at 22 percent and
Sawyer third with just 10 percent.
   Republicans have yet to name a candidate for the April 4 general
eelction.
   One main reason Sawyer's black support lags is that the City
Council coalition that elected him acting mayor a year ago was made
up largely of anti-Washington white aldermen.
   Evans, who was Washington's floor leader in the council and
claims to be his only heir, argues that Washington would never have
made such an accommodation with his foes.
   ``They have forgotten that everything we got for ourselves, we
got by fighting for it,'' Evans said, ``not because we decided to
unite with our enemy.''
   But Sawyer has amassed a $2 million campaign chest, compared with
less than $100,000 for Evans, and his campaign strategists are
betting an advertising blitz will force Evans out of the Democratic
primary.
   ``I'm in the chair and I'm not a quitter,'' Sawyer said. ``I'm
not going to walk away.''
   Daley, meanwhile, has had the luxury of remaining above the fray,
quietly building a war chest of his own. He has demurred when asked
about a mayoral run, but several Democratic committeemen say he is
simply waiting for Monday's court ruling.
   ``He's told me that he'll run,'' the Sun-Times quoted an
unidentified Daley source as saying. ``And he doesn't care who else
is in the race.''
</TEXT>
