<1ST_LINE>u i AM-LeukemiaVictim Bjt   11-20 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Leukemia Victim, Bjt,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Soviet Heads To United States For Leukemia Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pale and seriously ill former paratrooper left
the Soviet Union on Sunday for the United States, where he hopes a
network of support set up by his uncle in Moscow might save his life.
   Alexander Muchnik, 20, of Klaipeda in the Baltic republic of
Lithuania, is suffering from leukemia and his 15-year-old sister,
Viktoria, is the only source of the bone marrow needed for a
transplant that couldn't be performed in the Soviet Union.
   Before boarding a plane for New York on Sunday, the siblings,
their mother and stepfather said good-bye to friends and relatives.
Among them was Alexander's uncle, Ilya, a 50-year-old Moscow
computer scientist who built a network of medical help stretching
from Moscow and Amsterdam to the United States.
   Muchnik, whose pale complexion and sparse moustache give him the
appearance of a young student rather than a veteran of the Soviet
army's paratroop force, said simply, ``We'll see,'' when asked about
his prognosis.
   In the Soviet Union, doctors could only promise him a death
without pain.
   In the United States, the family planned to be united with
Alexander's grandmother, who emigrated years ago and now lives in
Brighton, Mass., and two aunts who live nearby. On Tuesday, Muchnik
has his first appointment with a Boston doctor.
   Ilya Muchnik said so far they have raised only a few thousand
dollars to cover a complicated operation that will cost about
$100,000.
   ``The question about financing the operation remains open,'' he
said. ``I think I have about three weeks. But three weeks, that's
the limit.''
   He said Dr. Dean Buckner, a Seattle specialist who examined
Alexander on a trip to Moscow and has followed the case since,
estimated the operation had an 80 percent chance of success if
performed in the very near future. But he said the chance of success
will fall sharply after that.
   In early October, doctors in Lithuania spotted a deformation of
cells that signaled a severe worsening of Muchnik's condition, his
uncle said.
   When Muchnik fell ill in July, shortly after being released from
the army, his uncle prevailed upon two well-known Soviets,
sociologist Tatyana Zaslavskaya and economist Abel Aganbegyan, to
help him find a place for his nephew in a top Moscow hospital.
   Doctors in the Netherlands analyzed blood samples and determined
that his sister could donate bone marrow.
   A long-time friend of Ilya Muchnik, computer science professor
Semyon Meerkov of Ann Arbor, Mich., found American doctors who took
an interest in the case and started a bank fund in the Michigan city.
   Friends from Canada, the United States, West Germany, Hungary and
Poland sent medicine that is not produced in the Soviet Union.
   U.S. Embassy officials in Moscow processed the necessary visas,
which the family received Nov. 14. The young man and his family are
traveling to the United States as immigrants, a decision spurred by
the illness.
   Muchnik's uncle said the family was held back at first because
Alexander and Viktoria's natural father would not sign waivers
allowing them to leave the Soviet Union, but he consented when told
of his son's illness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881120-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-88 1455EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MansfieldProfile     11-20 0878</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mansfield Profile,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mansfield Saga: Frugality to Fame and Influence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Mansfield, who got his first look at Asia
from a troopship as a teen-age serviceman, 66 years later is winding
down a formidable career of public service and strong influence on
U.S.-Asian relations.
   Mansfield told a Tokyo news conference last week he will retire
before the end of the year after a record ll years as U.S.
ambassador to Japan, the country he often describes as the most
important of all in America's future.
   Now 85, the former teen-age runaway, seaman, Marine, miner,
college professor, U.S. representative, senator and ambassador said
his decision to retire was made jointly with his wife, Maureen Hayes
Mansfield.
   By mentioning her, Mansfield was sharing credit for his story of
rags-to-fame and influence in America.
   As a grade school dropout back from service abroad in the Navy
and Marines, Mansfield got a job in the deep copper mines of Butte,
Mont., where, he once recalled, his schoolteacher bride ``put some
sense into me, told me to go to school and make something of
yourself, and I did.''
   The future ambassador was born in New York City of Irish
immigrant parents. His mother died when he was 3 and his father, a
hotel porter, sent him to live with relatives in the rugged Western
state which he represented in the Senate.
   ``I never thought I could get a college education because I left
school _ ran away before I finished the eighth grade _ and joined
the Navy at the age of 14 in the first (World) War'' by lying about
his age, Mansfield once told an interviewer.
   Still working in the mines, he enrolled at Montana School of
Mines and in 1933 at the age of 30 graduated from the University of
Montana. There he became an instructor and later professor of Asian
and Latin American history. Decades later, as ambassador, he liked
to tell Japanese he was once a professor. Montana U's main library
is now the Maureen and Mike Mansfield Center.
   Miners, teachers and Montana trade unions provided the Democratic
Party political base that sent Mansfield to Congress for 34 years,
the last 16 as Senate Democratic leader. As a freshman congressman
in 1944, he was included in a presidential mission to China. At the
end of the war, he was among lawmakers advising retention of the
emperor in Japan.
   Retiring from Congress in 1976, Mansfield returned from a
monthlong visit to China urging America to accept the ``reality'' of
communist rule. Mansfield argued that Beijing factions pushing
revival of the Soviet-Chinese alliance would grow stronger unless
the United States normalized relations with the mainland, even at a
cost of breaking official ties with Taiwan.
   Two years later, the United States took those steps.
   Mansfield earned a reputation in the Senate as a master of gentle
persuasion and compromise while criticizing U.S. participation in
the Vietnam War and scolding Secretary of State Henry Kissinger in a
soft-spoken style that became Mansfield's trademark. He is
remembered for informal Saturday morning gatherings open to any
reporters who cared to drop into his office in the Capitol.
   After President Jimmy Carter named him ambassador to Japan, Sen.
Robert Byrd, Mansfield's successor as Senate majority leader, joked
that Mansfield in Tokyo would turn the tables and ``give our friends
in the East the opportunity to study an inscrutable American.''
   Concerned by growing trade friction, Mansfield soon after
arrival, made the oft-repeated statement that the U.S.-Japanese
bilateral relationship is the most important in the world, ``bar
none,'' and that the collision course of the 1930s must be avoided
at all costs. The U.S.-Japan security alliance prompted him to liken
Japan and America to copper miners working underground in pairs,
each responsible for his partner's life.
   Mansfield tried to explain Japanese sensitivities and
complexities to American visitors, and to urge U.S. business to
compete more aggressively and seek long-term rather than instant
profits in Japan.
   This promoted some American critics to say Mansfield was too
conciliatory. But defenders said that to the Japanese he was always
plainspoken and made it clear they were certain to trigger U.S.
protectionism unless they opened markets and dismantled trade
barriers. Portraits of congressional leaders adorned Mansfield's
Tokyo office as a reminder of who wielded much of the power in
Washington.
   The U.S. trade deficit with Japan ballooned during most years of
Mansfield's ambassadorship but newly elected President Reagan's 1981
decision to keep the former Democratic senator in Tokyo was widely
applauded as an effort to depoliticize the issue.
   Protectionist pressure came from Democrats and Reagan apparently
felt it ``very useful to keep a Democrat in Tokyo who was close to
his policy line and enormously respected in Japan,'' said Dr. Martin
E. Weinstein, director of Japan programs at Washington's Center for
Strategic and International Studies, a private nonpartisan research
organization. ``I think Mansfield has done an excellent job and
clearly hasn't given into Japan-bashing at times when it was
fashionable.''
   In 1977, Mansfield's first year as ambassador, the U.S. worldwide
trade deficit was 25 billion dollars, 6 billion of it with Japan.
More than a decade later, the last annual figures were 170 billion
worldwide and 57 billion with Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
