<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Floods     11-20 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Floods,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Task Force To Study Ways Of Stemming Flooding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bangladesh and India agreed Sunday to
update their flood warning systems and seek ways to prevent
devastating floods like the ones that killed more than 1,000 people
in the summer.
   ``Although this is a problem of Bangladesh, India is trying to
help the situation for common benefit,'' Indian Water Resources
Secretary Naresh Chandra told reporters after the first meeting of
the Indo-Bangladesh Task Force.
   Bangladesh's mightiest, most flood-prone rivers start in India
and Nepal.
   Floods are a recurring problem in Bangladesh, a low-lying nation
of river deltas, but this year's were the worst in memory. About
three-fourths of the country was covered by water up to 16 feet deep.
   The task force, established Sept. 19, is to meet in New Delhi
next month.
</TEXT>
