<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hall of Fame pitcher Carl Hubbell was in
critical condition Sunday after his car struck a metal pole,
authorities said.
   Hubbell, 85, apparently suffered a heart attack or stroke that
caused him to lose control of the vehicle Saturday, police said.
Hubbell, who suffered a heart attack in 1977, was taken to
Scottsdale Memorial Hospital-Osborn.
   The left-hander, who lives about one mile from the accident
scene, won 253 games for the New York Giants from 1928 to 1943. He
struck out Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Jimmy Foxx, Al Simmons and Joe
Cronin in succession during the 1934 All-Star Game. All five are in
the Hall of Fame, which admitted Hubbell in 1947.
   Hubbell was known as ``King Carl'' and ``The Meal Ticket'' and
was famous for his screwball.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Model Paulina Porizkova, who recently signed a
reported $5 million to $6 million contract with Estee Lauder, says
she dislikes modeling and only does it for the money, but she admits
worrying about aging.
   Porizkova, 23, also said she ``eats like a horse'' and during a
recent breakfast interview consumed a doughnut, coffee cake,
buttered toast and coffee with cream.
   ``Beauty can get a woman what she wants: love and money. But when
beauty leaves you, so can the things it brought,'' she said. ``I'm
not thrilled about getting older. But I'm already facing up to the
irreversibility of the aging process.''
   Porizkova said she's learned to ``sew great curtains, paint,
build dollhouses, act and write.'' Her boyfriend, Ric Ocasek of the
rock group The Cars, ``thinks I lost my true calling to be a
librarian. I'm always reading.''
   ``You always think your last job is your last job,'' she said of
modeling. ``Then they turn their backs on you and say you don't look
good anymore, that you're getting older. They assume you're deaf,
they you don't have ears to hear. They tear you apart, detail by
detail. It's very cruel.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Embargoed until 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lisa Marie Presley, the daughter of Elvis
Presley, says her life has come together after a period in which she
dropped out of high school and experimented wiht drugs.
   ``I have a life of my own now and a man I want to share it
with,'' Presley said in the December edition of Life magazine.
   Presley said her father's drug use ``never changed my love for my
dad,'' and she described her own drug use as part of her
``rebellious stage.''
   ``I have to learn things by myself. I learned my lesson, and I
won't go near drugs again,'' she said.
   Presley dropped out of school in the eleventh grade. ``Even after
I quit doing drugs, I never went back. I regret it now,'' she said,
adding that she plans to take correspondence courses.
   Presley, 20, and musician Danny Keough, 23, were married in
October and are expecting their first child.
   Priscilla Presley said her daughter has turned out to be ``a
great kid.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Jeffrey Archer, who won record libel
damages against a London newspaper, says he is writing a satirical
play about how journalists battle for stories.
   ``Exclusive'' will open in London's West End next September,
Archer said Sunday.
   The play is set in Wapping, the east London district where many
Fleet Street newspapers have relocated, Archer said. It covers one
week in the life of a fictious tabloid, The Daily Chronicle,
following eight news stories through the eyes of 16 characters.
   Archer said the play does not seek revenge for newspaper
allegations he had a sexual liaison with a prostitute. A jury in
1987 awarded him about $800,000, the biggest libel award in British
history.
   ``My new play is just a witty, cheeky and irreverent Fleet Street
satire,'' Archer said.
   ``Absolutely not one line in it is for revenge. ... The trial was
18 months ago. It took me about a week to get over it. Now I just
don't give it a minute's thought.''
   Archer's best-selling novels about power and intrigue include
``Kane and Abel'' and ``First Among Equals.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC correspondent Sam Donaldson on Saturday
said George Bush will probably keep the news media at arm's length
the way President Reagan does.
   ``The presidency is closed down,'' Donaldson told a meeting of
journalists here, referring to Reagan's habit of barring or limiting
access to the presidency.
   Donaldson warned that the Bush administration probably will
continue ``the sequestering of the president from the press.''
   The ABC White House correspondent, who soon will leave that post
to host his own news program for the network, spoke at the national
convention of the Society of Professional Journalists, Sigma Delta
Chi.
   Donaldson has become known for asking tough questions and for
shouting them at Reagan when the president is boarding his
helicopter. Such tactics have drawn attacks from Reagan supporters
and criticism from other news people.
   But Donaldson said that presidents have set the rules for
journalists.
   ``Don't shoot at (the correspondents) because they're trying to
get access,'' he said. ``It's the presidents who've made it into
theater.''
</TEXT>
