<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Iraq-Archaeology     11-20 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Iraq-Archaeology,0136</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Expedition Finds Remains Of Assyrian City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British archaeological expedition has
found the remains of an ancient Assyrian city in the Jazira region
near the Syrian border, its director said Sunday.
   Warwick Ball said the main discovery was a ziggurat, a temple
built in the shape of a terraced pyramid.
   The team unearthed clay tablets relating the 247-acre site to the
Assyrian city of Telluleh.
   ``It is rather a small city but the find is exciting,'' Ball
said. He said the site was inhabited as long as 6,000 years ago.
   At its height in the 7th century B.C., the Assyrian Empire
stretched from Egypt across Mesopotamia to the shores of the Persian
Gulf. Its rulers were known as fierce military commanders and
efficient administrators.
</TEXT>
