<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0661 11-20 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Continue Marching After Largest Rallies In Yugoslav
History</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf pvs, ``Security forces...'' with 1 graf to
UPDATE with crowd dispersing. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``Up to...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of ethnic Albanians marched
in a blizzard through this provincial capital on Sunday in defiance
of government orders to end a wave of ethnic unrest and street
demonstrations.
   The demonstrations in the southern province of Kosovo are the
biggest there since World War II.
   Sunday's protests, the fourth straight day of unrest since the
forced resignation of two ethnic Albanian leaders, started when
about 500 chanting students braved the snow to march on the
headquarters of Kosovo's Communist Party.
   Waving Yugoslav flags and ethnic Albanian emblems, the crowd
swelled to about 4,000 within two hours, roaming city streets and
gathering outside a student canteen and party headquarters.
   The crowd first ignored an order by security forces to disperse,
but the demonstrators later began leaving the city center and it was
quiet by 8 p.m.
   Up to 100,000 people marched from dawn until midnight Saturday to
protest Thursday's resignations of Azem Vlasi and Kacusa Jasari,
members of Kosovo's 13-member ruling Politburo.
   Police blocked roads into Pristina late Saturday to prevent more
protesters from joining the boisterous crowds that demonstrated
almost continously since Vlasi and Jasari resigned.
   Snow fell through the night, driving chanting columns of
protesters off the streets, and increased police patrols appeared on
the streets Sunday.
   The province's acting Communist Party head, Remzi Koljgeci, tried
to defuse the tension by announcing Saturday night that the
resignations might be reviewed and reversed. But he also warned that
``extraordinary measures of security'' could be introduced if
demonstrations continued.
   ``In the past three days, we went through a situation which we
could not control,'' he said in a television interview Sunday
morning.
   Slobodan Milosevic, the Communist Party chief of the republic of
Serbia, which controls Kosovo, put what Vlasi called ``terrific
political pressures'' on him and Jasari to resign as part of his
campaign for more control over the autonomous province.
   Kosovo, which is dominated by an ethnic Albanian population, is
the heartland of Serbia's medieval empire. The Slav minority,
composed of 200,000 Serbs and Montenegrins, alleges it is being
harassed by the 90 percent Albanian population.
   On Saturday, Milosevic was honored by hundreds of thousands of
Serbs at a rally in Belgrade, the capital of both Yugoslavia and
Serbia. The Belgrade Communist Party daily Politika said the
demonstration was the largest in Yugoslavia's postwar history.
   Milosevic's supporters claimed 1.3 million people attended the
rally to express solidarity with Milosevic and the Slavs in Kosovo.
The Communist Party daily Vjesnik suggested 600,000 people ``would
be closer to reality'' as the number who attended the rally.
   In his speech, Milosevic vowed the Serbs would not stop until
their battle for Kosovo is won.
   Milosevic has antagonized non-Serb Communist leaders with his
campaign, which they fear may only be the first step toward
increasing the already powerful role of Serbia, Yugoslavia's largest
republic, in federal affairs.
   After the Belgrade rally, Milosevic and Koljgeci spoke by
telephone and agreed on undisclosed measures to calm the situation
in Kosovo, the official Tanjug news agency reported.
   The demonstrations in Kosovo were the largest there since the
communists came to power after World War II.
   Provincial leaders warned at a meeting Saturday night that, while
they hoped to control the situation Sunday, they feared more unrest
when workers return to work on Monday.
   Television reports said two or three demonstrators were briefly
detained Saturday for reportedly chanting demands that Kosovo become
a full-fledged republic. The country is made up of six republics and
Serbia's two provinces of Kosovo and Vojvodina.
   An estimated 500 ethnic Albanians are in jail on charges of
spreading counterrevolution by allegedly demanding independence from
Serbia.
   One ethnic Albanian student was heard shouting Saturday, ``What
are we waiting for when our people are rotting in jail?''
   The simmering ethnic strife in Kosovo, a backward region
bordering communist Albania, heated up over the summer when Serbs
staged a series of mass rallies to back Milosevic's campaign for
more control over Kosovo.
   Kosovo won broad autonomy under the 1974 constitution. Milosevic
wants that changed to restore Serbian control over education, the
judiciary and security in the province.
</TEXT>
