<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OPEC     11-20 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Urge OPEC Ministers to Reach Agreement, Boost Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of the United States'
energy-producing states urged OPEC on Sunday to reach a new
production accord so crude prices can rise and help their states'
ailing economies.
   ``We're fighting for our lives,'' J.E. Jumonville Jr., a
Democratic state senator from Ventress, La., told a news conference.
``It's a major part of our economic survival.''
   Ministers of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
tried in a third day of closed-door talks to resolve a dispute
between Iraq and Iran that has been delaying work on a new
production agreement.
   The accord would limit the amount of oil each of the 13 OPEC
countries could produce in an attempt to limit breakneck production
that has caused a glut and sent prices downward.
   Oil Minister Rilwanu Lukman of Nigeria, the cartel's president,
said a proposal was on the table, but he gave no details.
   ``The discussions are continuing,'' said Sheikh Ali Khalifa
Sabah, the Kuwaiti oil minister. ``We are here to find a solution.''
   The negotiations preceded Monday's start of the cartel's winter
meeting.
   Jumonville and other representatives of U.S. energy-producing
states met with OPEC members to appeal for price stability.
   The 12-member delegation represents the South-West Energy Council
and the Interstate Oil Compact Commission. Members of the delegation
are from Louisiana, Arkansas, Texas, Oklahoma and Alaska.
   Texas Railroad Commissioner Kent Hance told reporters he wanted
to have ``a dialogue with people that have more say on the Texas
economy than anything that's decided in our state capital or our
national capital.''
   The plunge in prices in 1986 badly damaged the economies of U.S.
oil states. There is concern a recent fall in prices could lead to
another downturn.
   ``We feel that our economy in Texas is starting to turn around,
but if oil prices went to single-digit numbers, it would stop us
from having a turnaround,'' he said.
   The officials said if prices rose to $18-$20 a barrel, it would
help their economies.
   ``It wouldn't be a boom for us, but it would allow us to
survive,'' Hance said.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, settled at $13.60 a barrel on Friday.
   OPEC maintains a benchmark price of $18 a barrel, although Arab
crudes have been running about $10 a barrel.
   The recent weakness in prices has been blamed partly OPEC
production that has surged to its highest monthly level in five
years.
   The current output accord, worked out in 1986, sets total OPEC
output at about 15 million barrels a day. But total cartel
production in October was estimated by the International Energy
Agency at nearly 21.1 million barrels.
   The accord covers only 12 members because Iraq refused the daily
quota of 1.5 million it was assigned, insisting that it be raised to
the 2.4 million given its bitter enemy, Iran.
   Since the two countries agreed to an August cease-fire in their
8-year-old war, efforts have been made to return Iraq to the quota
system.
   Formal talks between the two OPEC committees _ price evolution
and long-term strategy _ began Thursday.
   Cartel members are Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran,
Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, United Arab
Emirates and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
