<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WorldHelloDay     11-20 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Hello Day,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Hello Day Draws International Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT SONNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says he plans to say hello.
So do Douglas Fairbanks Jr., Itzhak Perlman, Jimmy Carter and George
Bush.
   They are among the hundreds of world leaders, entertainers and
others who agreed to do their part Monday to promote the 16th annual
World Hello Day by greeting 10 strangers with a pleasant ``hello.''
   The tradition began in 1973 when two Omaha brothers got the idea
they wanted to do something to encourage world peace.
   ``World Hello Day is a unique opportunity for people to do
something personal, memorable and enjoyable for the advancement of
peace,'' said Michael McCormack, 36.
   ``The attention we are getting shows what just one day like this
can do to transcend all the geo-political divisions that exist in
the world,'' he said in an interview Sunday.
   The brothers received an express letter from the White House on
Thursday with a ``warm hello'' from President Reagan.
   ``In reaching out to others in friendship, you spread the spirit
that is the foundation for peace within the home, the community, the
nation and the world,'' Reagan said.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson wrote that the brothers ``represent the
essence and the spirit of peace because you personally took the
initiative to do something in the name of peace.''
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis said a simple ``hello'' has
the power to span generations and traverse the globe. He cited a
favorite Chinese proverb _ ``A journey of a thousand miles begins
with a single step.''
   ``World Hello Day may well be the first step on a journey that
leads to peace on our planet,'' the former presidential candidate
said in a letter to the brothers.
   Past participants included Mother Teresa, Bishop Desmond Tutu,
Lech Walesa, Anwar Sadat, Oscar Arias, Prince Charles, Indira
Gandhi, Pope John Paul II, Luciano Pavarotti, Lee Iacocca, Charlton
Heston, Stevie Wonder and Arnold Palmer.
   Tass, the Soviet Union's official news agency, conducted two
telephone interviews with McCormack and his brother, Brian, 31.
   ``I was stunned for about 15 minutes after those two calls,'' he
said.
   ``Also, with official letters from Zaire and the Yemen Arab
Republic, the number of governments who have contacted us with
letters of support has risen to 101,'' he said.
   Everyone is encouraged to participate, McCormack said.
   ``Participating in World Hello Day is a symbolic action, which
celebrates the contributions made by personal communication to the
resolution of conflicts and the preservation of peace,'' he said in
a promotional flier.
   McCormack said he came up with the idea while attending Harvard
University in response to rising global tensions. The first year,
representatives of 15 countries wrote back to him saying they had
participated.
   ``We certainly hoped it would be successful but the magnitude has
surprised us,'' he said.
   McCormack has worked full-time recently on promoting the
observance.
   ``I just decided to save up some money and do the best job I
could this year on World Hello Day. We're not quite like Gandhi, but
we're not rich folks. We've spent several thousand dollars on this.
I do it full-time _ night and day since June,'' he said.
   McCormack said accounts of Monday's ``hellos'' are to be
broadcast by the BBC, Radio Netherlands, China News Service,
Hungarian News Agency and State Publishing House of Mongolia.
   ``To see this happening around the world is just amazing,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
