<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SunkenHistory     11-20 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sunken History,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historians Seek Clues From Sunken Ship in Lake Michigan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Historians are hoping to learn more about
the glory days of Great Lakes shipping from a well-preserved wreck
that sank more than a century ago and was discovered recently in
Lake Michigan.
   Two divers found the 200-foot wooden schooner Wells Burt over the
summer, said Kurt Anderson, a board member of the Chicago Maritime
Society, which wants to help recover artifacts to learn more about
shipboard life.
   The divers have decided to keep the ship's location secret for
now to prevent it from being plundered by artifact hunters, Anderson
said.
   Ship traffic was heavy on the Great Lakes in the 1800s and many
of them sank during storms, he said.
   The Wells Burt sank in 1883 off Evanston, a suburb north of
Chicago, while heading to Chicago with a load of coal, he said. Its
11 crewmen died. The ship may have been coming from Buffalo.
   The wreck is under nearly 50 feet of water and is resting next to
a rock ridge that protects it from currents, Anderson said. The
ship's deckhouses and masts were ripped off in a storm that sank the
vessel.
   Anderson said he has seen a videotape of the wreck and it is in
good shape.
   ``The deck is pretty much in place and there's a lot of things
that are still on board,'' he said. ``Hopefully the crew's quarters
are still intact so we can look into shipboard life,'' he said.
``We'd like to find personal effects of the people who were sailing
on her.''
   While shipping on the Great Lakes in the 19th century was a major
industry, little is known about sailors' lives aboard merchant
ships, he said.
   ``We want to put together an exhibit about the ship and its
times,'' Anderson said.
   The first step is mapping and charting the wreck to find where
everything is and then recovering artifacts, he said.
</TEXT>
