<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Baltics     11-20 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Baltics,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Says Estonians Used Pressure To Pass Amendment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Estonian activists put undue pressure on their
legislators and resorted to threats to win approval for a challenge
to the Kremlin's authority over their Baltic republic, an Estonian
lawmaker was quoted as saying Sunday.
   In an interview with the Communist Party daily, Vasily Koltakov,
an ethnic Russian and one of seven deputies to vote against the
measure Wednesday, portrayed the unprecedented action as excessive
and dangerous to ethnic relations.
   The Estonian Supreme Soviet, or parliament, approved an amendment
to the republic's constitution requiring that any new Soviet laws be
approved by local authorities. They also passed a ``declaration of
sovereignty'' in all areas except foreign affairs and defense.
   Koltakov, a factory worker, told Pravda that ``on the eve of the
session there was an overt `coaching' of deputies.''
   Koltakov said the People's Front, the Estonian organization that
sponsored the amendment, advised him to ``abstain from voting when
they learned about my stand.
   ``Moreover, as one of the women deputies told me, unidentified
persons telephoned her on the eve of the session and uttered threats
to make her cast an `aye' vote.''
   Felix Undusk, a spokesman for the People's Front, said the Pravda
interview was read in Estonian on the republic's official radio on
Sunday.
   ``That's propaganda pressure,'' Undusk said in a telephone
interview from Tallinn, the Estonian capital. ``I can't say there
was any such strong pressure.''
   A Soviet parliamentary committee ruled Saturday that the Estonian
action was at odds with the national constitution. On the same day,
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev said during his visit to India that
``what is happening in Estonia is perestroika,'' his program of
social and economic reforms.
   In the Pravda interview, Koltakov said the People's Front was
taking Gorbachev's reforms too far.
   Some members of the organization openly have called for a halt to
emigration of other ethnic groups into Estonia or even repatriation
to their home areas.
   According to the last census, 61 percent of Estonia's 1.5 million
people are ethnic Estonian, and 28 percent are Russian.
   ``Hundreds of thousands of people of non-indigenous nationalities
have come to feel like `lodgers' unwelcome to the hosts,'' Koltakov
said.
   But Undusk said the People's Front, which has gained thousands of
members and the support of high government and Communist Party
officials in Estonia, will not back down.
   ``There won't be any other decision,'' he said. ``We are standing
on our own.''
   The drive for autonomy in Estonia has spread to the two other
Baltic republics, Lithuania and Latvia. Residents of the three
republics, which together have a population of less than 10 million,
are clamoring for greater control over their economic and cultural
life under the banner of Gorbachev's reform effort.
   Legislators in Lithuania on Friday proclaimed Lithuanian, the
mother tongue of about 80 percent of the republic's population, the
official language and restored the flag of the independent republic
that existed until 1940.
   On Sunday, about 140 leaders of the independent Lithuanian
Movement for Perestroika proclaimed the ``moral independence'' of
their republic from Soviet laws, said spokesman Alvydas Medalinskas
in a telephone interview from the capital of Vilnius.
   But Lithuanian legislators have been discouraged from taking
action similar to Estonia's by the chief of their Communist Party,
Algirdas Brazauskas.
   The small, Westward-looking republics were independent until
1940, when they were deeded to the Soviet Union under a secret
agreement between Hitler and Soviet leader Josef Stalin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
