<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   11-20 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0648,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Killed, Six Youths Shot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with soldier killed in accident in Lebanon,
more Palestinians wounded, Shamir statement; CORRECTS that
9-year-old among five beating injuries in 2nd graf; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops raided Palestinian settlements in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip on Sunday, fatally shooting a 22-year-old
man and wounding six Arab youths in clashes, Arab hospital officials
said.
   Five Palestinians suffered beating injuries during an army raid
in the West Bank village of Madama, Arab doctors said. The injured
included a 9-year-old boy with head wounds, they said, adding that
the cause of the injuries was not known.
   The army command confirmed that there was ``activity'' in Madama
but said it had no reports of injuries.
   Three Israelis suffered injuries when buses they were riding in
were pelted with rocks in the West Bank.
   In Lebanon, an Israeli soldier was killed and four others injured
when their armored personnel carrier overturned Sunday in southern
Lebanon, the army said. ``It was a road accident,'' said an army
spokesman, who declined to elaborate.
   Israel radio said the accident occurred north of the Lebanese
city of Naqoura, two miles north of the Israeli border in Israel's
self-declared buffer zone. The zone is patrolled by about 1,000
Israeli troops and the 2,000-member South Lebanon Army.
   Meanwhile, underground PLO leaders distributed leaflets praising
the declaration of an independent Palestinian state last week by the
Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile.
   The leaflet said the Palestine Liberation Organization had seized
a historic opportunity to boost the 11-month-old uprising against
Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. The pro-PLO
leaders also urged Moslem fundamentalist extremists to stop
criticizing the declaration publicly.
   ``Whether you like it or not, that will serve the enemy,'' said
the leaflet, signed by the Unified National Leadership of the
Uprising.
   The pro-PLO leaders called for ``escalating the struggle''
against Israel in the next two weeks and announced three one-day
strikes.
   Egypt on Sunday became the latest nation to recognize the
Palestinian state. A statement said it hoped the proclamation would
``serve the cause of peace and stability in the region.''
   ``I regret it very much,'' Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres
said about Egypt's stand. He declined further comment until he
studied the Egyptian statement.
   At least 31 other nations, mainly Moslem, have recognized the
state.
   In Jordan, Prime Minister Zaid Rifai said the PLO has met
conditions for taking part in the Middle East peace process by
implicitly recognizing Israel's right to exist, and accused Israel
of blocking a settlement.
   Sunday's Palestinian fatality occurred during an army raid of the
West Bank village of Baqa, near Nablus, said officials at Nablus' Al
Ittihad Hospital.
   Troops encountered resistance from Palestinians and opened fire,
wounding Yousef Mohammad Abdallah in the head and shooting a
16-year-old in the shoulder. Abdallah died at the hospital, Al
Ittihad officials said.
   His death raised to 314 the number of Palestinians killed in the
uprising. Eleven Israelis have been killed.
   At the El-Ein refugee camp near Nablus, a 17-year-old Arab youth
was shot in the hand, hospital officials said.
   Also in the West Bank, three Israelis were slightly injured in
stone-throwing attacks on public buses at the Amari refugee camp
near Ramallah and in the biblical town of Hebron.
   Israel's military administration said it will gradually start
reopening about 1,200 schools in the West Bank in December, but
warned schools will be shut down again in case of student
demonstrations.
   In separate clashes in Gaza's Jabaliya and Shati refugee camps,
soldiers shot and wounded four teenagers, hospital officials said.
   The 1.5 million Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip have been engaged since last December in an uprising against
21 years of Israeli military rule. Israel captured the territories
from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East War.
</TEXT>
