<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CuomoLanding 2ndLd-Writethru a0665 11-20 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuomo Landing, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0665,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Carrying New York Governor Lands After Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Another state...', with 4 grafs to add detail
on second pilot helping governor's plane. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `In
July...'. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plane carrying Gov. Mario Cuomo made an
emergency landing at a small Pennsylvania airport early Sunday after
occupants of the plane reported smelling smoke, a spokesman said.
   Nobody was injured in the incident, which happened about 1:30
a.m., said Gary Fryer, a Cuomo spokesman. It was the third time
since July 1987 that the twin-engine state plane has been forced to
make an emergency landing.
   After the Democratic governor and his aides reported smelling
smoke, the two pilots turned off all non-essential power, including
the aircraft's interior lights, Fryer said. Using flashlights to
read their controls, the pilots then landed at the Williamsport
airport, which was closed at the time.
   The governor's spokesman said it was still unclear Sunday whether
there was a fire aboard the plane.
   People who had been on board said the smell was like that of an
electrical fire, he said, but ``it could just have been overheated
wires smoldering.'' At the same time, the plane's pilots reported
some problems with the radio, Fryer said.
   The pilots were assisted by an unidentified pilot in another
plane and by air traffic controllers in New York City, Boston and
Altoona, Pa., said Fryer.
   Because of the electrical problems, the governor's plane's radios
and navigational equipment were not working properly, said Fryer. So
the unidentified pilot helped out by relaying information from air
traffic controllers to the governor's pilots, he said. The pilot
also used his equipment to turn on the runway lights at the closed
airport, he said.
   ``We don't know who the good samaritan was, but whoever he is, he
was very helpful,'' said Fryer.
   After Cuomo's plane landed safely, another state plane flew to
Williamsport and returned him to Albany at about 6:30 a.m. Sunday,
said Fryer. Cuomo had been flying from New Orleans, where he
addressed the Council of Jewish Federations on Saturday night.
   In July 1987, pilots made an emergency landing at the Albany
County Airport when a light indicated an engine fire on the
Grumman-made G-1. That incident occurred shortly after Cuomo and his
entourage took off for a National Association of Governors meeting
in Michigan. An inspection revealed that the light had malfunctioned
and there was no fire.
   The plane then underwent a $628,000 overhaul after Cuomo
concluded it would be too expensive to replace. Then, there was an
emergency landing in March while the speaker of the state assembly
was on board, again because of a malfunctioning warning light.
   The two-engine turbo-prop aircraft had ``a substantial amount of
work done'' on it after the first incident last year, Fryer said.
``But like any aircraft, it's subject to problems.''
   Cuomo was traveling Sunday with two assistants and a State Police
bodyguard, Fryer said.
</TEXT>
