<2ND_LINE>AM-Song Banned,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pop Song Falls Foul of IRA Broadcast Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British authorities have banned a song by the
popular Irish folk group The Pogues because its lyrics support 10
people convicted of IRA bombings, a newspaper reported Sunday.
   The ban was issued under an order imposed last month by Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher's government. The order prohibits
broadcast interviews with members of the outlawed Irish Republican
Army, 10 other militant groups and their sympathizers.
   The Observer, a London weekly, said Britain's Independent
Broadcasting Authority ordered all commercial radio stations not to
play the band's single ``Streets of Sorrow@Birmingham Six.''
   Pogues manager Frank Murray was quoted as saying he stood by the
song's lyrics, which say the 10 were ``picked up and tortured and
framed.''
   The Broadcasting Authority said the lyrics might ``invite support
for an organization proscribed by the Home Secretary's directive in
that they (the lyrics) indicate a general disagreement with the way
in which the British government responds to, and the courts deal
with, the terrorist threat,'' according to the newspaper.
   Six Irishmen have claimed they were beaten into confessing and
convicted on faulty forensic evidence of killing 21 people in two
IRA pub bombings in the central England city of Birmingham in 1974.
It was the worst terrorist attack in modern British history.
   Three other Irishmen and an Irish woman have professed innocence
for two IRA pub bombings that killed five people in Guildford near
London the same year. Their lawyers say they too were convicted
after forced confessions and that the jury never heard evidence in
their favor.
   All 10 were sentenced to life in prison.
   Last month's ban followed an upsurge in killings by the mainly
Roman Catholic IRA. The rebel group is fighting to end British rule
in the Protestant-dominated province of Northern Ireland and unite
it with the predominantly Catholic Irish Republic to the south.
</TEXT>
