<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile     11-20 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Denounces Pinochet Threat to Annul Election
Results</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCEPCION, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition leader said Sunday that
President Augusto Pinochet would lose the backing of the armed
forces if he tried to overturn a referendum requiring him to call
open elections.
   Pinochet, the army commander, said Saturday said that the outcome
of the Oct. 5 presidential referendum would become invalid if his
opponents refused to abide by a constitution drafted in 1980 by his
military government.
   Patricio Aylwin, leader of the centrist Christian Democratic
Party, told reporters in Concepcion that Pinochet's statement
``makes me think this gentleman is not really assuming his
reponsibility as leader.''
   Referring to Pinochet's comments about canceling the referendum
results, Aylwin said, ``He couldn't do it, because I'm certain that
the armed forces would not back any thing like that.''
   Aylwin, a 69-year-old lawyer, is considered to be the most
probable presidential nominee of an opposition coalition. The
Christian Democrats are Chile's largest single political
organization.
   In the referendum, Chileans rejected a proposal that would have
kept Pinochet in power until 1997. The vote was 3.9 million against
and 3.1 million in favor.
   As a result, the constitution requires that Pinochet call
elections, planned for December 1989, and hand over power to the
winner in March 1990.
   Since its victory the opposition has pressed for constitutional
amendments it says are needed to assure full democratic powers for
the new government. They contend the constitution gives too much
power to the presidency and to the military.
   Pinochet has said he will permit no changes. On Saturday, in the
southern city of Coyhaique, he said of the opposition: ``I have
asked them if they accept the constitution, but they remain silent.
If they say `No,' the plebescite is null.''
   The 72-year-old army commander seized power in a 1973 coup that
ousted the elected government of Marxist President Salvador Allende.
   Aylwin called Pinochet ``a president who has been beaten, to whom
the people have said they no longer want, and who finds himself more
and more alone.''
</TEXT>
