<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BikeMan     11-20 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bike Man,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighborhood Bike Man Gives Up After Kids Steal Bikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Detamore never had a bicycle when he grew
up in a family of 14 children, so he spent 40 years making sure
other kids do. But he's decided to stop giving out bikes because
neighborhood kids keep stealing them. The last straw came when his
dog was shot with a pellet gun.
   ``I know if I keep (the bikes), I'll hurt someone,'' said
Detamore, 78. ``So I'm just giving them away.''
   His wife, Marie, says her husband lost his desire to collect and
repair bicycles when ones he intended to give to needy children
began disappearing at night.
   Bicycles filled all but a small path in the Detamores' backyard
and lined both sides of their driveway until he gave about 600 bikes
Saturday to the city, which hopes to continue Detamore's charitable
mission.
   His bike collecting began when his sons wanted one.
   ``I couldn't afford new, so I got some old ones and fixed them
up,'' he said. ``It wasn't long before every kid in the neighborhood
was pushing his bike up the alley for me to fix.''
   He'd take old bikes, find the parts and repair them. He asked
only for money for the parts. But if a child didn't have the money,
that was fine, too.
   ``It was just something for me to do,'' said Detamore, who is
retired.
   Now, he plans only to repair bikes with the spare parts that fill
every available nook and cranny of his garage.
   ``I can't stop altogether,'' Detamore said.
</TEXT>
