<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoundaryWatch     11-20 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boundary Watch,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suburban Schools Battling Increase Of Illegal Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City students fleeing gangs and low-quality
education are improperly attending suburban schools, which are using
educators and off-duty police officers to catch the impostors,
authorities said Sunday.
   Efforts to find students posing as suburban residents include
staking out train stations and following students home.
   ``We've caught 75 kids this year who live outside the district
and the money it cost us to educate them could translate into three
more teachers,'' said Larry Walker, assistant principal of Oak
Park-River Forest High School.
   Under state law, youngsters who live in one school district may
attend a public school in another area if they pay tuition. Student
impostors thus are costing school districts and taxpayers thousands
of dollars, officials said.
   At Walker's school in Oak Park, located just west of Chicago city
limits, annual tuition for students from other districts is $6,944,
Walker said.
   Other suburbs report similar problems.
   ``Last year it cost $5,049 to educate students and this year
we've found about 25 students who don't belong here and are not
paying tuition,'' said Raymond Surges, assistant principal at
Proviso East High School in Maywood.
   ``If we catch four students, that's one teacher we could hire,''
he said. ``It's a burden that the board of education and the
taxpayers don't want to deal with.''
   When they are caught, impostor students are withdrawn from the
school and ordered to enroll in the district where they live, Surges
and Walker said.
   ``When we find them we ask them to surrender their school
identification so they can't get into the building,'' Surges said.
   Students who want to get into a suburban school sometimes find
someone with the same last name in a telephone book and take the
address as their own or claim they are living with ailing relatives,
the educators said.
   ``I've heard an awful lot of dying grandmother stories,'' Surges
said.
   Parents seeking better educations for their children usually are
behind the problem, Walker said.
   ``The time we see this the most is when the Chicago schools are
on strike,'' he said. ``Most parents are honest, but if it's a
choice of no school or lying to get their kids into Oak Park, a lot
will decide to lie.''
   Illinois law requires that once a student is suspected of
attending classes illegally, officials must allow parents an
opportunity to prove they and the youngster live in the district.
   ``The burden of proof goes to the parent to prove residence,''
Walker said. ``We ask to see leases or utility bills. Parents have
to convince us. They're suspect.''
</TEXT>
