<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Election-Mondale     11-20 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Election-Mondale,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mondale Says Presidential Campaign ``A Disgrace''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Walter Mondale says the
presidential campaigns run by both candidates this year were ``a
disgrace'' and turned out ``worse than I originally thought.''
   ``I feel sick,'' Mondale said of the George Bush and Michael
Dukakis campaigns in an interview published in Sunday editions of
the Star Tribune.
   Mondale said part of the blame should go to television, which
revealed more about campaign media handlers than about the
candidates themselves.
   ``There is no substance,'' Mondale said of the campaign. ``The
candidates are hidden. You don't get to ask questions. The negatives
have taken over and it's mud every night.''
   Mondale said he was especially angered by a news conference at
Boston Harbor where Bush declared himself an environmentalist,
labeled Dukakis a polluter and then put a halt to questions.
   ``Politicians are permitted to throw mud from privileged
sanctuaries and the negatives are driving substance off the playing
field,'' he said. ``They can mount an attack and then not take
questions about that attack. First Bush, then Dukakis. You couldn't
get a hold of any of them for questioning and for context.''
   Mondale called for more frequent and longer debates than the two
sessions held this year, in which he said Bush and Dukakis delivered
scripted lines and ignored substantive questions.
   Mondale predicted the problems he identified wouldn't be resolved
until people get fed up with show-business presidential campaigns.
   ``Maybe it's starting,'' he said, noting that this year's voter
turnout was only about 50 percent.
</TEXT>
