<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wet, Stormy Weather Dominates The East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wet weather dominated the eastern third of the nation Sunday with
heavy rain over parts of the Northeast, Florida and the Ohio Valley,
after a night of strong tornado activity.
   A low pressure system was centered over Ohio and thunderstorms
developed along a cold front that extended from the low southward
into the Florida Panhandle.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed near the low over
southwestern, central and eastern Ohio into western West Virginia.
Wind from a thunderstorm downed trees at East Liverpool, Ohio.
   Gusty wind was reported with the passage of the cold front, with
gusts to 56 mph at Cincinnati, 53 mph at Columbus and to 52 mph at
Huntington, W.Va.
   One to two inches of rain was measured across southern Ohio
including 1.95 at Piketon, 1.92 at Salem Center and 1.65 at Athens.
Louisville, Ky., reported 1.41 inches in 24 hours.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were along the cold front over
Georgia and the Florida Panhandle, producing brief heavy rain over
parts of the Florida Panhandle.
   During the six hours up to 1 p.m., 1.33 inches of rain fell at
Panama City, Fla.
   During the previous night, 23 tornadoes were reported over the
South, and two people were killed in Mississippi.
   Rain also was widespread from southern Lower Michigan into New
England and the mid Atlantic Coast region. Northern New Jersey got 1
to 1.75 inches of rain and Newark had a record 1.31 inches by
midmorning. Bridgeport, Conn., got 1.32 inches of rain in the six
hours up to 1 p.m. and New York City got 1.30 at LaGuardia airport.
   Snow fell over much of the middle Mississippi Valley region, with
5 to 7 inches on the ground at Rolla, Mo. Three inches fell in the
St. Louis area.
   Scattered light snow fell from the Dakotas into Minnesota.
   Elsewhere, light showers were scattered over the Idaho Panhandle
and northwestern Montana.
   A tropical depression in the Caribbean was upgraded Sunday to
tropical storm Keith, the 11th named storm of the hurricane season.
   Jacksonville, Fla., reached a record 85 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 14
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 87 at Daytona Beach and St.
Petersburg, Fla. Sunday morning's low was 12 degrees below zero at
Jackson, Wyo.
   For Monday, snow was forecast from northeastern New York state
into much of Maine, with scattered snow showers in western and
central New York state. Widespread rain was forecast over the
northern and central Pacific Coast, with showers scattered across
the Pacific Northwest and northern plateau regions and snow
spreading across northwestern Montana.
   Highs in the 30s were predicted from the northern high Plains
through the upper Mississippi Valley and the Great Lakes region into
the northern half of New England; in the 60s from western and
central Texas through the Gulf Coast region into the middle and
southern Atlantic Coast, and over central and southern California;
in the 70s across the Los Angeles basin, southwestern Arizona, the
lower Rio Grande Valley and central Florida; in the low 80s over
southern Florida; and in the 40s or 50s across much of the rest of
the nation.
</TEXT>
