<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Elections     11-20 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Elections,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters Elect Mayors in Two States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in the central and southern states of
Tlaxcala and Chiapas on Sunday cast ballots in more than 150
municipal races, and opposition parties accused the government of
fraud.
   The governing Institutional Revolutionary Party has not lost a
major election in its 59-year history and was expected to win most
of the mayoral races. Many of the municipalities are in remote
regions and final results were not expected to be announced until
next week.
   Mayors were being elected in all 109 towns and cities in Chiapas
and in the 44 in Tlaxcala.
   ``If the vote is respected _ and it's not being respected _ there
would be the possibility of victories in at least 20
municipalities,'' Jorge Moscoso Pedrero, an official of the leftist
National Democratic Front in Chiapas, said by telephone.
   The governing party ran candidates in all of the contests. The
Democratic Front had candidates in 43 municipalities in Chiapas and
the conservative National Action Party was entered in 21.
   In Tlaxcala, the Democratic Front parties had candidates in 33 of
the 44 municipalities and the National Action Party 12.
   Moscoso Pedrero said, ``We have reports of `flying brigades,' all
traveling in pickup trucks of the Agriculture Department'' going to
different polling places and voting in each one in Villa Flores, 35
miles southwest of the provincial capital of Tuxtla Gutierrez.
   Similar allegations were made by the opposition in the July 6
general elections. PRI officials denied the claims.
   The governing party candidate, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, won the
presidential election with an official tally of 50.36 per cent of
the vote and will succeed President Miguel de la Madrid on Dec. 1.
</TEXT>
