<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pakistan-Elections     11-20 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Elections,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Provincial Voters Give Bhutto's Party Mixed Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The party of populist leader Benazir
Bhutto virtually swept voting in its home province but shared
regional power with rivals in three other provinces, according to
election results released Sunday. Ms. Bhutto's left-of-center party
won the largest bloc of seats in National Assembly elections last
week and moved her closer to her goal of becoming prime minister.
She had hoped Saturday's follow-up provincial elections would allow
her to consolidate her political power.
   She said Sunday she was pleased with the showing of her Pakistan
People's Party in Saturday's voting.
   ``We feel very happy about these elections,'' she told a press
conference at her walled compound in the southern port city of
Karachi. ``They are a tribute to the people of Pakistan.''
   With all but a handful of 459 precints reporting results from
Saturday's voting, Ms. Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party gained 184
provincial seats, compared to 145 for the right-wing Islamic
Democratic Alliance, its strongest rival. The remainder went to
independents and minor parties.
   In her home province of Sind, Bhutto's party virtually shut out
the Democratic Alliance with a 67-1 victory in provincial Assembly
seats.
   Ms. Bhutto's party appeared likely to be able to form a slim
majority coalition in two other provinces, Baluchistan and Northwest
Frontier.
   However, the Democratic Alliance captured a 108-94 victory over
the People's Party in Eastern Punjab, where 60 percent of the
country's 107 million people live.
   With the country's first free elections in more than a decade
complete, Pakistanis now look to President Ghulam Ishaq Khan to name
a prime minister. He has not said when he will do so.
   Ms. Bhutto says her party has attracted enough support outside it
ranks to form a government. She would be the first woman to lead an
Islamic country.
   However, her conservative rivals in the Democratic Alliance say
that despite their weaker showing in the national election, they too
can form a coalition big enough to command a majority.
   Ms. Bhutto's populist party won 92 seats in Wednesday's voting
for the National Assembly, while her main rivals won 55 in the
237-seat body.
   Ms. Bhutto, 35, is the daughter of former Prime Minister Zulfikar
Ali Bhutto, was ousted by Gen. Mohammed Zia ul-Haq in 1977 and
executed two years later.
   Zia died Aug. 17 in a plane crash soon after calling elections.
</TEXT>
