<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Scarfo     11-20 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scarfo,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Scarfo, 16 Others Guilty In Racketeering Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor in mob boss Nicodemo ``Little
Nicky'' Scarfo's racketeering trial says the conviction should send
a message that the government can get tough on organized crime.
   A federal jury on Saturday night convicted Scarfo, 59, and 16
associates in a racketeering conspiracy that included murder, drug
dealing, loansharking and illegal gambling.
   The five-lawyer Organized Crime Strike Force that prosecuted the
case rejoiced after the verdict was read.
   ``I think everyone of us was quietly confident,'' said Assistant
U.S. Attorney Louis Pichini, who led the team. ``We were so terribly
proud that the system worked and did not buckle under.
   ``We were confident that the case had the evidence to convince a
reasonable jury and this jury was convinced overwhelmingly. One of
the things that this case did was it broke the myth of the Mafia's
invincibility.''
   Scarfo's attorney, Robert Simone, said he would appeal the
verdict reached after 26 hours of jury deliberations.
   Each defendant was found guilty on each of the two main
conspiracy counts they faced. In addition, some were found guilty on
other charges they faced individually.
   All the defendants face up to 20 years in prison. No sentencing
date was set.
   The government contended the 17 defendants were mobsters who
conspired in nine murders, four attempted murders, extortions, drug
dealing, loansharking and illegal gambling.
   Defense attorneys had attacked the credibility of the
government's star witnesses, ex-mobsters Thomas ``Tommy Del''
DelGiorno and Nicholas ``Nicky Crow'' Caramandi, who have testified
in previous trials against Scarfo.
   The case began Sept. 13 and was heard before U.S. District Judge
Franklin Van Antwerpen.
</TEXT>
