<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     11-20 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers And Students Rally, Demand Chun Punishment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of teachers and students
called Sunday for educational reforms and demanded that former
President Chun Doo-hwan be punished for alleged misdeeds during his
authoritarian rule.
   About 10,000 educators and students demonstrated peacefully
outside the National Assembly building to demand laws be revised to
prohibit government interference in education.
   ``Abolish undemocratic educational laws,'' the protesters yelled.
Many demonstrators also shouted slogans demanding Chun's arrest for
corruption, misrule and human rights abuses.
   President Roh Tae-woo, beset with mounting calls for Chun's
punishment, has been pressing his predecessor to surrender property
and retire to the countryside in a traditional gesture of repentance.
   There has been a spate of street protests urging Chun's arrest in
recent weeks. On Saturday, thousands of students and dissidents
battled riot police in downtown Seoul when police stopped their
march to Chun's house.
   Opponents also charged that mutinous army generals, including
Roh, worked out an elaborate scenario in 1980 that enabled Chun to
seize power during martial law.
   In a parliamentary hearing late Saturday, meanwhile, lawmakers
quizzed former Defense Minister Choo Young-bock about the alleged
roles Chun and the United States played in putting down the 1980
civil uprising in the southern city of Kwangju.
   Opposition lawmakers claimed Chun and his associates provoked the
uprising to catapult Chun to the presidency. The Kwangju tragedy
remained a political tinderbox during Chun's seven-year rule.
   Choo shrugged off most opposition allegations Saturday but
apologized to the nation for failing to prevent the Kwangju
violence, in which nearly 200 people were killed.
   Choo also testified that the South Korean military worked
independently to put down the uprising, although the United States
had operational control of South Korean forces under the two
nation's mutual defense pact.
   ``There is no reason for the United States to intervene in
domestic affairs,'' Choo said.
   But opposition lawmakers produced military records they claimed
indicated that U.S. forces had prior discussions with Korean army
generals and approved the dispatch of troops to Kwangju.
   Top opposition leader Kim Dae-jung said Friday that the United
States could not avoid moral responsibility for bloodshed in Kwangju.
   The opposition-controled National Assembly opened hearings Nov.
7., the first in South Korean history. The hearings have been
broadcast live on national television and have drawn large audiences.
</TEXT>
