<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Religious     11-20 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Religious,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres: Labor Won't Deal Over `Who Is A Jew' Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres told a group of
American Jews on Sunday that his Labor Party will never make a
political deal that would alter Israel's criteria for determining
who is legally Jewish.
   An amendment supported by the rival Likud bloc would give
Orthodox rabbis the exclusive authority to approve conversions to
Judaism. The proposal is strongly opposed by Conservative and Reform
Jews.
   ``We could not have built Israel without American Jews,'' Peres
told a delegation from the New York-based National Council of Jewish
Women. ``We must continue to keep our people together.''
   Representatives of the women's council said they are concerned
that some Israeli parties are willing to use the ``Who is a Jew''
amendment as a political bargaining point.
   ``This amendment would disenfranchise Jews all over the world,''
said Nan Rich, a member of the council's national board of
directors. ``It would alienate many of us who feel we have a great
stake in the future of Israel.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc has told
Israel's religious parties it would support the amendment. The
religious parties are a crucial factor in forming a coalition
government.
   Religious parties won 18 of the 120 seats in Parliament in the
Nov. 1 election and neither Likud nor the left-leaning Labor
acquired a majority, with Likud winning 40 seats and Labor 39.
   Peres declared that his party would not change its position on
the ``Who is a Jew'' issue even if it joins a coalition government
led by Likud.
   ``We will never negotiate away our right to remain true to our
positions,'' Peres told reporters after the meeting with the
American delegation.
   The proposed amendment would change the Law of Return that gives
Israeli citizenship to any Jew who seeks it.
   Current law defines a Jew as anyone born to a Jewish mother or
converted to Judaism. The change would nullify conversions performed
by Reform and Conservative rabbis, disqualifying a majority of the
six million Jews in North America.
   Earlier Sunday, 1,000 British members of the international Joint
Israel Appeal opened its annual fundraising drive in Jerusalem with
a call to abandon the ``Who is a Jew'' amendment.
   Trevor Chin, president of the group in Britain, said changing the
Law of Return would damage relations with Jews around the world. He
said on Israel radio, ``Israel has a constituency of world Jewry
that is unified.... For God's sake don't break it.''
   In Atlanta, Ga., Reform leaders urged Israel to reject the
efforts by Orthodox parties to amend the Law of Return.
   The board of trustees of the Union of American Hebrew
Congregations, meeting in Atlanta, sent a letter to Israeli
President Cjaim Herzog, Shamir and Peres saying: ``We implore you,
for the sake of Israel and the Jewish people, to put Jewish unity
before considerations of political expediency.''
</TEXT>
