<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ChessOlympiad     11-20 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chess Olympiad,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sweden Ties Soviets in Chess Olympiad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALONICA, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sweden held the Soviet Union to a 2-2 tie
in the seventh round of the Chess Olympiad on Sunday, but the
Soviets kept a 2.5-point lead in the championship.
   In separate women's competition, the Soviets regained the lead
from Hungary with a 3-0 victory over West Germany. They seized a
1.5-lead as Hungary, the overnight leaders, lost 2-1 to Yugoslavia.
   The first Soviet defeat in the men's championship came when
Swedish International Master Thomas Ernst gained an impressive
victory over Grandmaster Jaan Ehlvest.
   The Soviets tied the match when former world champion Anatoly
Karpov beat Sweden's top player Ulf Andersson.
   The Soviets maintained first place with 22 points. Sweden, the
ninth seed, was second with 19.5 points.
   Yugoslavia, which was ahead 2-0 against Bulgaria with two games
unfinished, was third with 18.5 points.
   Harry Schussler, Sweden's second-ranked player, said the 2-2 tie
with the Soviets left Sweden with a strong chance to win a medal.
   West Germany crushed Poland 4-0 to move up and share fourth place
with East Germany, Netherlands and third-seeded Hungary.
   The United States, who won the bronze medals in the last three
Olympiads, on Sunday drew its match with East Germany 2-2.
   Boris Gulko of the United States defeated Uwe Boench, but the
East Germans tied with a victory from Rainer Knaak over Larry
Christiansen.
   The biggest surprise of the day in the men's competition came
when India, the 21st seed, took a 2-1 lead over second-seeded
England.
   One victory came from International Master Krishnamoorthy
Murugtan, who overpowered British Grandmaster Jonathan Mestel.
   But England has a chance to tie the match. Grandmaster Murray
Chandler has adjourned a pawn ahead in an endgame against Dibyendu
Barua.
   The Hungarian women's team, favored by many experts to win the
gold medals over the Soviets, collapsed when Ildiko Madl lost
against Yugoslavian International Master Suzana Maksimovic.
   It was the first match where Hungary had rested Judit Polgar, the
highest ranked 12-year-old in history.
   The 28th Olympiad, a biennial world team championship, is being
held in this city about 300 miles north of Athens. Organized by the
127-member World Chess Federation, the month-long competition
features teams from 106 nations.
   The 14th and final round is scheduled for Nov. 29.
   The adjourned games will be completed Monday with the eighth
round on Monday evening.
</TEXT>
