<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainDerailment     11-20 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Derailment,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Evacuees Return After Acid Neutralized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARDEN CITY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people returned home Sunday
after an overnight evacuation that began when a train derailed and
spilled nearly 30,000 gallons of sulfuric acid.
   Four engines and 73 cars _ 42 loaded and 31 empty _ jumped the
tracks at 5:30 p.m. Saturday as the CSX train traveled north from
Birmingham to Nashville, Tenn., officials said.
   Most of the contents leaked from a 30,000-gallon tanker
containing acid, producing fumes that irritated lungs and eyes. An
estimated 1,000 people from Garden City and Bangor, about 35 miles
north of Birmingham, were evacuated, said Chief Deputy E.C. Ellard
of the Cullman County Sheriff's Department.
   ``It was a precautionary measure, but no one was injured,''
Ellard said.
   Crews built a levee to contain the leaking acid and then used
lime to neutralize it.
   Some of the acid leaked into a creek, which feeds into the
Mulberry Fork River, but it was not enough to be dangerous, said Lee
Helms, director of operations for the Alabama Emergency Management
Agency.
   John Walker, a CSX Transportation spokesman in Jacksonville,
Fla., questioned the county's evacuation count, and said railroad
officials estimated it at no more than 200.
</TEXT>
