<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     11-20 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamils Win Majority in New Provincial Council</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Tamil organizations won 18 seats
and a Moslem party won 17 in balloting for a a new administrative
council in war-ravaged eastern Sri Lanka, election officials said
Sunday.
   Tamil guerrillas battling for a separate homeland boycotted
Saturday's election in Eastern province.
   Military officials said at least 40 people were killed in
election-related violence Saturday and Sunday, including six members
of the Indian peacekeeping force that provided security at polling
stations. The officials, who were not identified according to
government policy, gave no other details.
   Sinhalese, who form a majority in most other areas of this island
nation and control the national government, did not win any of the
35 council seats.
   Lakshman Perera, deputy election commissioner, said two Tamil
groups, the Eelam People's Revolutionary Liberation Front and the
Eelam National Democratic Liberation Front, received 215,230 votes
and 18 seats.
   Both had been guerrilla organizations but renounced violence and
accepted the peace accord mediated by India in an effort to end the
fighting that has taken more than 8,500 lives since 1983.
   Perera said the Sri Lanka Moslem Congress won 168,038 votes and
17 seats while the predominantly Sinhalese United National Party got
8,056 votes.
   There were 635,050 eligible voters but the most powerful Tamil
guerrilla group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, called for a
boycott. The Liberation Tigers said that the plan, which merged the
Northern and Eastern provinces with a semi-autonomous 71-seat
administrartive council, did not meet their demands for their own
homeland.
   Eastern province has large Sinhalese, Tamil and Moslem
communities while Northern province is overwhelmingly Tamil.
Northern province named its 36 members to the administrtavie council
last month. There were no elections there because the Tamil factions
agreed on a formula for apportioning the seats and all candidates
were unopposed when nominations were filed.
   Most Tamils are Hindus and many accuse the Buddhist Sinhalese of
discrimination. Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of Sri Lanka's
population of 16 million people and the Tamils about 18 percent.
</TEXT>
