<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Haiti To Get Emergency Hurricane Relief Aid, Other Funds Released</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The United States will give Haiti
about $3 million in emergency hurricane relief and release $5
million in other aid, a spokesman for the U.S. Embassy said Sunday.
   Spokeswoman Susan Clyde said the hurricane aid will be in the
form of food and heating oil. Agricultural production in the
southern peninsula of Haiti was severely damaged by Hurricane
Gilbert in September.
   The United States also is releasing $5 million in food relief
money under a program called the Food for Peace.
   The United States froze $20 million in Food for Peace money after
last year's violently aborted elections, but $15 million were
released last month.
   The U.S. government cut off about $60 million in non-humanitarian
aid to Haiti after last year's aborted elections.
   ``About $30 million in humanitarian aid has never been cut off,''
Clyde said.
   The total U.S. aid package to Haiti was about $90 million.
   At least 34 people were slain Nov. 24 when thugs shot and hacked
to death voters while army troops looked on. Haiti at the time was
under the rule of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, who was deposed Sept. 17 in
a coup by lower-ranking officers. Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril was
installed in Namphy's place.
</TEXT>
