<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-88 2117EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-McNamaraProbe     11-20 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-McNamara Probe,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McNamara Says He Won't Resign Over Marijuana Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney Frank L. McNamara Jr. said Sunday he
will not resign despite a Justice Department investigation into
allegations that he lied when he said he saw his predecessor smoke
marijuana.
   ``This is a mountain out of a molehill,'' McNamara said. ``I
think the whole thing has been a tremendous amount of nonsense. You
can look for that office to continue to function as a professional
office with me at the helm.''
   McNamara also said his own use of marijuana as recently as four
years ago did not run counter to tough anti-drug pronouncements.
   ``What I did is what a lot of people who grew up and went to
college in the '60s and '70s did. I wish I hadn't done it. I'm not
happy I did it. It was a mistake,'' he said.
   ``Perhaps out of that I can be even more committed to the war
against drugs,'' he added.
   McNamara, 41, the chief federal prosecutor for Massachusetts,
faces a Justice Department inquiry into his claim to investigators
that his predecessor, William F. Weld, smoked marijuana at a 1982
party in Virginia while still U.S. attorney.
   The Justice Department reported last week that an inquiry found
evidence to contradict McNamara's assertion.
   ``I want any questions that may exist in anybody's mind about my
motivations in this entire matter to be resolved,'' McNamara said in
a telephone interview from his home in Bolton. ``That's why I
requested the investigation.''
   McNamara refused to discuss the inquiry by the department's
Office of Professional Responsibility or his accusations against
Weld, whom McNamara succeeded in April 1987.
   McNamara said he planned to hold a staff meeting Monday to
discuss the charges, which aides said have virtually paralyzed the
50-lawyer office that prosecutes all federal crimes in Massachusetts.
   McNamara took over as U.S. attorney several weeks afer Weld left
for Washington to head the Justice Department's criminal division.
   The federal probe is examining whether McNamara made up the
marijuana story because Weld had opposed his nomination on grounds
that other prosecutors had more experience. It also reportedly is
examining whether McNamara was forthright about smoking marijuana
when he was questioned prior to confirmation for the job.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
