<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DavisTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0742 11-20 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Davis Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,0671</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Larry Davis Acquitted of Attempted Murder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf, `Maybe there,' with reax from
district attorney; picking up 5th graf pvs `The Nov.' Note contents
of 4th graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who got into a wild shootout with police
who tried to arrest him and then spent 2{ weeks in hiding was
acquitted Sunday on attempted murder charges, but convicted of
weapons violations.
   It was the second time this year that Larry Davis has been
acquitted in a trial. On March 3, he was found innocent of murdering
four suspected drug dealers in the Bronx.
   When the verdicts were announced, Davis squeezed the hands of his
lawyers, Lynne Stewart and William Kunstler, according to Kunstler.
Tears came to Davis' eyes, said Kunstler, the leftist lawyer who
often portrays black clients like Davis as victims of a racist
system.
   ``Maybe there will be no more black Sambos, only black Rambos,''
Kunstler said. ``Maybe this means there will be fewer shootings of
blacks and young Latinos in this city.''
   Bronx District Attorney Paul Gentile said he would ask the judge
to give Davis the maximum sentence on the weapons counts, in the
hope that ``it will help those police officers who received
devastating injuries accept these verdicts.''
   ``The devastating fact remains that this jury of 12 people, by
their verdict, found that the injuries that Larry Davis imposed upon
these police officers in the course of their duties were justified
by law,'' Gentile added.
   The Nov. 19, 1986, shootout occurred when 20 officers went to
Davis' sister's apartment to arrest him for the four drug-related
slayings.
   Davis, now 22, escaped unscathed from the apartment after trading
more than 30 shots with nine officers. He was captured after a
17-day manhunt, one of the most extensive in the city's history.
   Prosecutors said Davis opened fire to evade arrest. The defense
contended officers went to kill Davis because of his knowledge of
police corruption, and that he fired in self-defense.
   In addition to the nine counts of attempted murder, Davis was
acquitted of six counts of aggravated assault.
   The jury, which deliberated for five days, convicted Davis on six
counts of criminal possession of weapons, said Ed McCarthy,
spokesman for the Bronx district attorney's office.
   Davis faces a maximum penalty of 10 to 20 years in prison on the
weapons counts when Acting Justice Bernard Fried imposes sentence.
In unrelated cases, Davis still faces two charges of murder.
   A key issue was who fired first _ the police or Davis. The
defense said it was a shotgun-wielding officer, presumably one who
rushed in ahead of other officers; prosecutors said it was Davis,
whom they portrayed as a murderous crack dealer.
   Kunstler said the testimony of a ballistics expert showed that
the first shot came from a police shotgun at close range _ closer
than the prosecution maintained.
   ``The truth of this case is justification,'' defense attorney
Lynne Stewart told the jury during closing arguments. ``Against all
odds, Larry Davis, a son of the South Bronx, acted to save his life
in the back bedroom of his sister's apartment.''
   Testimony lasted four months, with the prosecution calling 56
witnesses, most of them police, and the defense calling 17.
   Jury selection began April 18 but pretrial maneuvers took months,
beginning with the prosecution successfully arguing that the defense
was arbitrarily excluding whites from the jury.
   The defense sought to establish that Davis had unusual contacts
with the police, presenting testimony that officers frequently
visited him at home the past five years. Prosecutors countered with
police witnesses who said they visited the Davis home in the course
of numerous criminal investigations.
   The defense also sought to show that the police fabricated the
grounds for the arrest party as an excuse to kill Davis. Prosecutors
countered by trying to establish that Davis was legitimately a prime
suspect in the four killings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
