<FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-88 2155EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     11-20 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Play Opens Based on Randy Newman Songs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randy Newman's songs, many of them satirical or
from an off-the-wall point of view, probably need a format for
theater different from a revue where it's just ``and then he wrote
...''
   ``The Middle of Nowhere,'' which opened Sunday night at the
off-Broadway Astor Place Theater, has a novel format _ the
washed-up-on-a-desert-island idea combined with the old-time
minstrel show. It sounds chancy but it works quite well. It's
simpler than it sounds, too.
   Brief program notes explain about the sections in 19th century,
white-glove minstrel shows. This allows Newman songs to be grouped _
love songs, songs about misfits, songs about money _ for a reason.
   Roger Robinson is whittling in an unused bus station when Vondie
Curtis-Hall as a soldier, Michael Arkin as a salesman, Diana Castle
as a Baltimore-bound hitchhiker and Tony Hoylen, carrying beer cans
in a guitar case, come in out of the rain. This gives them
individual identity. Miss Castle, for instance, is the logical
singer of Newman's ``Baltimore.''
   The show's two most inspired theatrical strokes are during the
songs ``Short People'' and ``Lonely at the Top.'' As Curtis-Hall,
Arkin and Hoylen fervently spout the nonsensical prejudice in
``Short People,'' a carnival distorting mirror is slid in behind
them on stage, turning their own reflections into the object of
their prejudice.
   ``Lonely at the Top'' has its universality furthered by having it
sung by Robinson, dressed as a janitor and pushing a dustmop.
   Newman put sarcasm and deep satire in ``Song for the Dead.''
Curtis-Hall sings the show's most thoroughly serious song, in his
Army uniform.
   Most of Newman's songs are devised so the satire brings a smile.
Curtis-Hall glides through ``It's Money That I Love'' as a slick
dance number. Arkin becomes an ugly American for the selfish ``Roll
with the Punches.''
   ``They Just Got Married'' was probably included to show that,
with Newman, you can't guess the ending of a lyric. Hoylen gets to
sing the funny ``Maybe I'm Doing It Wrong'' and the pretty ``Marie.''
   Tracy Friedman conceived, wrote, directed and choreographed. The
Back of the Bus Band, not seen, plays instrumental accompaniment.
Producers are Frank Basile, Lewis Friedman, Tom O. Meyerhoff and
Albert Nocciolino. ``The Middle of Nowhere'' was first produced by
the Wisdom Bridge Theater in Chicago.
   There's a lot of entertainment to be had in an evening in this
Louisiana town so small ``the gas station went out of business when
the diner shut down.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881120-0074 </DOCNO>
