<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GasPrices     11-20 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gas Prices,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gas Prices Drop A Notch At Nation's Pumps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline prices at the nation's pumps dropped
an average two-tenths of a cent over the past two weeks because of a
drop in wholesale crude prices and a return to seasonal driving
habits, an analyst said Sunday.
   The Lundberg Survey, a sampling of 12,000 service stations
nationwide, showed the average retail price of gasoline was $1.0006
on Friday, said analyst Trilby Lundberg.
   The average retail price includes all grades of self- and
full-serve gasoline, all taxes, and all cash and credit sales, she
said.
   In the Nov. 4 survey, prices had climbed two-tenths of a cent
because of increased wholesale prices and heavy gasoline trading.
   Ms. Lundberg predicted further price cuts as wholesale prices
continue to drop and winter keeps motorists home.
   On Nov. 18, the average price at self-serve pumps for regular
unleaded gasoline was 90.62 cents a gallon; premium unleaded was
$1.0604 a gallon; and regular leaded was 86.77 cents a gallon.
   The average price at full-serve pumps for regular unleaded
gasoline was $1.1922 a gallon; premium unleaded was $1.3016 a
gallon; and regular leaded was $1.1627 a gallon.
</TEXT>
