<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0649,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transport Strike Begins, Paralyzes Several Manila Districts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with strike in effect; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed soldiers guarded buses and
military trucks shuttled stranded commuters Monday as passenger jeep
drivers went on strike in the capital.
   Police and other officials said several routes were paralyzed
although service was operating near normal on others.
   The strike was called by PISTON, a militant association of about
25,000 passenger jeep drivers. The jeeps are the major means of
transport in the Philippines. Several other jeep associations have
announced they would join Monday's strike.
   PISTON has demanded a price roll-back of commodities and a
reduction in the cost of automotive spare parts following a
presidential decree last week to reduce fares.
   Mayor Jejomar Binay of Manila's financial district of Makati made
a last-minute appeal to striking drivers over government-run Radio
of Nation to end the strike.
   ``I wish to tell the drivers that they should give the government
a chance to prove its promises,'' Binay said. ``Prices of
commodities cannot be brought down overnight. We are doing our best
to bring prices of goods and spare down.''
   Patrolman Dick Calizo said at least 20 military trucks have been
sent out to help stranded passengers but no violence was reported as
of mid-morning.
   Classes at the University of Santo Tomas and other schools were
suspended for the day because of the strike.
   Radio DZMM said there had been reports of jeepney drivers
harassing other drivers who refused to join the strike which
resulted in several fistfights and stoning incidents.
   On Sunday, troops and police were placed on nationwide alert in
preparation for the transport strike and for celebrations marking
President Corazon Aquino's first 1,000 days in office, state-run
media reported.
   The state-run Philippines News Agency said Gen. Renato De Villa,
the military chief of staff, issued the order to prevent violence
during the strike.
   De Villa said armed troops would ride buses in the capital Monday
and that military trucks would prowl the streets to assist commuters
who may be stranded by the strike, government media said.
   Under the new transport fares, a passenger has to pay a minimum
of 3 cents for a 2.5-mile ride. The old rate was 4 cents, but
drivers actually charge a 5 cents.
   There was no explanation why the military was placed on alert
nationwide since the strike was called only for Manila and its
surrounding suburbs.
   But Monday marks Mrs. Aquino's first 1,000 days in office, and
military sources have said leftist or rightists opponents may try to
foment unrest to distract from official ceremonies marking the
benchmark date.
   Mrs. Aquino took office on Feb. 25, 1986, after a popular
uprising toppled the administration of Ferdinand Marcos and forced
the Philippine strongman to flee to exile in Hawaii.
</TEXT>
