<2ND_LINE>AM-Election-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Election At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Canada, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT number of seats formerly in House of
Commons to 282, sted 280</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on the Canadian election:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE STAKES _ Canadians are electing a House of Commons newly
expanded to 295 seats, so a party needs 148 seats to form a majority
government.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE VOTERS _ There are 17.1 million eligible voters. Polls open
from 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. in each district. Across the nation that means
they open at 7:30 a.m. EST in Newfoundland and close at 11 p.m. EST
in British Columbia.
   The first returns are expected about 9 p.m. EST, but it could be
well into the night before the outcome is clear. Voter turnout in
the last Canadian national election on Sept. 4, 1984, was 75 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE MAJOR PARTIES _ They are the incumbent Progressive
Conservative Party led by Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, the
opposition Liberal Party led by John Turner and the socialist New
Democratic Party led by Ed Broadbent. In 1984, the Conservatives won
211 seats, the Liberals 40, the New Democrats 30, and there was one
independent. The House of Commons then had 282 seats.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE KEY ISSUE _ The free trade agreement with the United States
scheduled to take effect Jan. 1 overshadowed all other issues in the
seven-week campaign. The Conservatives say the agreement will
guarantee future Canadian prosperity by securing access to the
larger U.S. market. The Liberals and New Democrats oppose the pact,
saying it endangers Canadian sovereignty and such crucial social
programs as senior pensions and health care.
   The U.S. Congress has approved the agreement, but it still needs
final Canadian parliamentary approval. Only a Conservative majority
government ensures that the agreement will proceed.
</TEXT>
