<HEAD>Jackson Requests Meeting With Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Sunday he was seeking a meeting
as soon as possible with President-elect George Bush to discuss
threatened farm foreclosures and the new administration's policy
toward South Africa.
   Jackson met with about 80 staff members, advisers and prominent
supporters to review the 1988 presidential campaign and to make
plans for his Rainbow Coalition political movement.
   At a news conference, Jackson urged Bush to speak out against
last week's treason conviction of four leading black activists who
belong to the United Democratic Front, South Africa's largest
anti-apartheid group.
   He also said that if Bush is committed to ``a kinder and gentler
nation'' he should call a moratorium on the foreclosures of family
farms.
   Earlier this month, the Farmers Home Administration began mailing
notices to more than 80,000 farmers who are past due on loans that
they risk foreclosure proceedings if they do not make arrangements
for settling their debts.
   ``We hope to meet with Mr. Bush at the earliest possible date to
put some primary focus on his making a statement appealing for mercy
and reasoning in South Africa, and mercy for the 90,000 family
farmers who received their notices ... one week after the
election,'' said Jackson.
   He planned to telephone Bush to ask for a meeting, said Jackson
spokesman Eric Easter.
   Jackson said he will be focusing next year on supporting
candidates whom he considers progressive in mayoral elections in
Chicago, New York, Los Angeles and other major cities.
   The former Democratic presidential hopeful said the Rainbow
Coalition would push its demands for an effective anti-drug
campaign, a higher minimum wage, a national health care system,
improved child care, and simplified, same-day voter registration
procedures.
   Jackson denied that liberal positions were responsible for
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis' loss to Bush, because the party
made gains in congressional and local races.
</TEXT>
