<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-PLO, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0729,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Egypt, China Recognize Palestinian State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with China recognition; picks up
6th graf: `In Jerusalem...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Jordan-Mideast, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt said it recognized the newly proclaimed
Palestinian state on Sunday and expressed hopes the declaration
would contribute to peace and stability in the region.
   China also announced Sunday it had decided to recognize the newly
declared state, its Foreign Ministry was quoted as saying.
   Egypt's statement came a few hours after Israel's ambassador,
Moshe Shamir, called on Foreign Minister Esmatt Abdel-Meguid to
brief him on the Israeli government's position regarding the newly
proclaimed state.
   The Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile,
proclaimed the state on Tuesday and also endorsed U.N. resolutions
242 and 338, implying recognition of the state of Israel.
   Israel has officially rejected the move, saying the Palestine
Liberation Organization has not explicitly recognized Israel nor
renounced terrorism.
   An Egyptian government communique said that ``as Egypt blesses
this constructive step, it hopes that it (the proclamation) would
serve the cause of peace and stability in the region.''
   The Chinese statement, carried by the official Xinhua News
Agency, said: ``The Chinese government, with full respect for the
choice made by the Palestinian people, has decided to recognize the
state of Palestine.''
   An initial Foreign Ministry reaction on Wednesday stopped short
of explicitly recognizing the new state but called for ``friendship
between the peoples of China and the state of Palestine.''
   In Jerusalem, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said Sunday he
regrets Egypt's decision. ``I regret it very much,'' he told
reporters.
   Peres said he had to study the Egyptian statement before making
further comment.
   Israeli officials have argued that Egypt would violate the 1978
Camp David accords between Israel and Egypt if it recognized the
Palestinian state.
   The U.S.-mediated Camp David pact called for the final status of
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip to be negotiated in peace
talks among parties to the Middle East conflict.
   The Egyptian statement, read to reporters and carried by the
state-run Middle East News Agency, said the recognition should be
effective Nov. 15, the day the PLO body proclaimed the state.
   The statement complained that ``some quarters'' have persisted in
casting doubt on Egypt's position of support.
   ``To uproot these doubts ... Egypt hereby affirms its recognition
of the Palestinian independent state according to the points that
came in the political statement issued by the PNC and considers this
recognition effective since Nov. 15.''
   On Saturday, the agency quoted President Hosni Mubarak as
expressing Egypt's recognition of the Palestinian state, but later
it amended its report, saying the word ``recognition'' was incorrect
and that Mubarak had only declared support for the establishment of
the state.
   More than 30 countries, mostly Moslem, have recognized the
Palestinian state.
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat pressed his efforts Sunday to gain more
recognition. He and Iraqi President Saddam Hussein urged non-aligned
countries to recognize fully the newly declared state, the Iraqi
News Agency reported.
   Monitored in Nicosia, the agency said both voiced ``satisfaction
over the historical decisions'' taken by the Palestine National
Council. The two were meeting in Baghdad.
   King Hussein of Jordan said Sunday the PLO has met U.S.
conditions to join in Arab-Israeli peace talks and suggested Israel
and the United States were blocking peace.
   ``I believe the PLO has gone as far as it was asked to go and has
contributed its share for progress toward a just and comprehensive
peace,'' he said on CBS television's ``Face the Nation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881120-0079 </DOCNO>
