<HEAD>China Recognizes Palestinian State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has decided to recognize the newly declared
independent state of Palestine, the Foreign Ministry said Sunday.
   ``The 19th special session of the Palestine National Council held
in Algiers on Nov. 15, 1988 proclaimed the founding of the state of
Palestine,'' the ministry said in a statement carried by the
official Xinhua News Agency.
   ``The Chinese government, with full respect for the choice made
by the Palestinian people, has decided to recognize the state of
Palestine.''
   China has long been a strong supporter of the Palestinian
Liberation Organization and Arab causes. It has said it will not
form diplomatic relations with Israel until the Israeli government
returns land seized during the 1967 Israel-Arab War.
   An initial Foreign Ministry reaction on Wednesday stopped short
of explicitly recognizing the new state but called for ``friendship
between the peoples of China and the state of Palestine.''
   The Palestine National Council, legislative wing of the PLO,
declared a new Palestine state with Jerusalem as its capital.
   More than 30 nations, most of them Moslem, said they recognized
the declaration.
</TEXT>
