<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Missile     11-20 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Missile,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudanese Officials Blame Missile Attack On Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials accused rebel forces
Sunday of firing the missile that hit a plane with the nation's
defense minister and other top-ranking military officials aboard.
   Brig. Gen. Mohamed Osman Malik, the military command spokesman,
said the SAM-7 surface-to-air missile was fired Saturday by rebels
of the Sudan People's Liberation Army.
   The pilot of the damaged Hercule C-130, which carried Defense
Minister Abdul-Maguid Khalil and military Commander-in-chief Gen.
Fathi Ahmed Ali, managed to land without any injuries. The plane had
just taken off from Wau in southern Sudan's Bahr el-Ghazal region.
   The attack came a day after a tentative cease-fire agreement was
signed in the Ethiopian capital of Addis Ababa between rebel leader
John Garang and a delegation from the second-largest partner in
Sudanese Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi's coalition cabinet. Mahdi
supports the agreement, but his ministers have not yet voted on it.
   The prime minister said Sunday that the attack proves the
southern-based rebels do not really want peace. ``The rebel movement
is not serious about its peace claims,'' he said. ``It has lost
credibility.''
   The rebels are demanding economic and social reforms for their
region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
