<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Brazil-Strikes     11-20 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Strikes,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Strike Leaders Urge Locals to End Crushing Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the nation's worst oil
strike called for local unions Sunday to accept a government offer
and return to work. They declared their strike a political success.
   The recommendation came after stocks of kitchen gas and diesel
fuel fell to critically low levels. In the northeast, bottled
cooking gas was rationed to one canister per household, and
elsewhere Brazilians waited in long lines or paid black-market rates
for a single canister.
   The Strike Command of the National Oil Workers recommended that
local unions accept the government's proposal for a 15 percent pay
raise. Strikers had asked for 26 percent.
   Unions nationwide were to vote through early Monday on whether to
follow the National Command directive, according to Command director
Carlos Gomes. He spoke to The Associated Press by phone from
Brasilia.
   ``We believe the government proposal is reasonable, although it
isn't ideal,'' Gomes said. ``We consider the strike, politically,
has been a complete success.
   ``We expect strikers will vote to go back to work (Monday),'' he
said.
   On Saturday, Petrobras, the government-run monopoly that runs
petroleum drilling and production, offered workers the pay raise to
make up for losses caused by a 1,000-percent annual rate of
inflation. Petrobras also said it would pay wages for five of 10
days workers have been striking, not punish strikers, and consider
rehiring workers fired in another walkout.
   Brazil has suffered a recent wave of strikes caused by a
sputtering economy under President Jose Sarney. The strikers have
included national park employees, doctors and nurses at
government-run clinics, electricity workers, subway personnel,
steelworkers and federal employees in at least 17 of 26 ministries.
   Civilian Liaison Minister, Ronaldo Costa Couto, told journalists
Sunday he hoped strikers would return to work Monday. He said the 15
percent wage increase represented ``the limit of government
possibilities.''
   During the strike, emergency stocks of cooking gas and diesel
fuel have been imported from Argentina, Venezuela and Algeria.
Gasoline supplies were expected to last another 20 days.
   Of Brazil's 10 refineries, three were partially operating Sunday,
and petroleum production stood at 350,000 barrels per day. At full
capacity, Brazilian refineries produce 1.5 million barrels daily.
</TEXT>
